NOTE: read this all!  this information is in no particular order, 
these are just notes added from time to time but don't need to be
really chronological  :-(

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
so far, some RECT_FILL (s3frect.c), BITBLTs and some text stuff has been
implemented (no lines and no image functions at all right now).

font cache doesn't work yet, so you have to make sure that either your 
virtual size is large enough that no space for font cache is available
or specify a smaller amount of memory in the device section.
I'm running 1024x768 8bpp and specified (1K needed for S3 hardware cursor):
    Videoram 769

using this setup xterm, twm and a few other clients work well enough 
to start some editing work in X11 itself (maybe).

right now clipping has been disabled for font display due to lockup 
problems I've to look closer to.

one more config note: since  image functions are not implemented yet,
the linear frame buffer test fails and thus the server crashes since
"newmmio" (the only access method for the ViRGE GE) needs it -- 
there are some more checks needed to avoid the crash...

to get the server started you have to specify the Membase in the config file
(see "scanpci" or "cat /proc/pci" output, must mbe 64MB aligned!!)
so my current device section looks like this:

Section "Device"
    Identifier "Victory 3D"
    VendorName "ELSA"
    BoardName "Victory 3D"
    Membase 0xe4000000
    Videoram 769
EndSection

most tests I only did for 8bpp sp far but 16bpp should be ok too.
24bpp needs more work, STREAMS processer has to be setup for packed 24bpp...

 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
newmmio.h:
all old SET_xxx definitions are NOPs so that they can be kept in the sources
for documentation until changed to new ones but don't harm

I've changed all old SET_xxx commands which I've worked on and I'm not sure if
completely/correctly replaces by new onces by ";SET_xxx" (so prepended by
a semicolon to be easily seen/greped etc).


all new defines to access the graphics engine (GE) are called SETo_xxx
where 
	o=B  for BITBLT/RECT, 
	o=L  for 2d lines, 
	o=P  for 2d polygon fill (not used at all right now), 
	o=L3 for 3d lines (n.u.)
	o=T3 for 3d triangles (n.u.)

I decided to use different defines/commands for BLTs and LINEs even when 
at the moment the ViRGE uses the identical registers for both parameter
sets but this might change in the future and this way it would be easier
to change things then.  
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

check s3InitEnvironment() in s3init.c first for some global settings
and initialisation.  
some of this should be moved elsewhere later (e.g. in s3Init() ?).

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

CLIPPING:  
I'd like to keep the clipping on the whole virtual screen and use it 
by the default "s3_gcmd" setting.
if access to off-screen memory is needed I'm using "s3_gcmd & ~CMD_HWCLIP".

when local clipping is needed, SETB_CLIP() should be reset to the virtual
scren at the end of the operation.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

conversion from S3 to S3V routines:

height of rectangles isn't specified "off by one" anymore:

	SET_AXIS_PCNT(w,h)  -->  SETB_RWIDTH_HEIGHT(w,h+1)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

accel/s3_virge/mio.c

is a small standalone program to play with memory mapped IO for debugging
purposes.  two small examples (for other see usage and source):

	mio ix 83d4 2f			get chip revision
	mio mx 83d4 66 ff 2  mx 83d4 66 ff 2	toggle CR66 bit1 (reset GE,
don't try this in text mode!!!)
	mio il 8504			reads SUBSYS_STAT
	mio ol a4f4 5 ol a504 00200010 ol a50c 02000100 ol a500 17e00120
			draw RECT at 512,256 with size 32,16 in color 5

but only access GE regs when the server is really idle, stopped, suspended
or similar!


pio.c  does the same for normal I/O  (shouldn't be necessary too often 
for ViRGE since VGA regs are mapped to 0x8XXX).
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

